revision.text:
'''Aaron Afia''' ({{Lang-he-n|אַהֲרֹן‬ אַפִיָא}}, ''Aharōn Afia''), also known as '''Affius''', was a sixteenth-century [[Jewish]] ex-''[[converso]]'' scientist, mathematician, philosopher, and physician living in [[Thessaloniki|Salonika]].

He was the teacher of Daniel ben Perachiah, whom he assisted in the translation from the Spanish into Hebrew of [[Abraham Zacuto]]'s ''Almanach perpetuum'' (1543), and [[Moses Almosnino]], whom he assisted in his (unpublished) Hebrew translation of [[Johannes de Sacrobosco]]'s ''[[De sphaera mundi]]''.<ref>{{cite book|first=Olga|last=Borovaya|title=The Beginnings of Ladino Literature: Moses Almosnino and His Readers|location=Bloomington|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2017|isbn=978-0253025524|lccn=2016024515|page=68|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=gsSCDgAAQBAJ}}</ref> Almosnino's ''Bet Elokim''—an astronomical work which draws on [[Georg von Peuerbach]]'s ''Theorica planetarium''—also contains work by Afia at the end.<ref name=bodies>{{cite book|chapter=Jewish Bodies and Renaissance Melancholy: Culture and the City in Italy and the Ottoman Empire|first=Eleazar|last=Gutwirth|title=The Jewish Body: Corporeality, Society, and Identity in the Renaissance and Early Modern Period|editor1-first=Maria|editor1-last=Diemling|editor2-first=Giuseppe|editor2-last=Veltri|location=Leiden|publisher=Koninklijke Brill|year=2009|isbn=978-90-04-16718-6|pages=57–92|url=https://books.google.ca/books/about/The_Jewish_Body.html?id=m1Lh-FwFrXIC}}</ref>

Affia main work is the ''Opiniones Sacadas de los mas Auténticos y Antiguos Philósophos que Sobre la Alma Escrivieron, y sus Definiciones'' ("Selected Opinions of the most Authentic and Ancient Philosophers on the Soul, and their Definitions"), published in Venice in 1568. It was appended to ''Los dialogos de Amor'', the Spanish translation of [[Judah Leon Abravanel|Judah Abravanel]]'s ''Dialoghi d'amore''.<ref name=EJ>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Afia, Aaron|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Judaica|edition=2|editor-first=Fred|editor-last=Skolnik|editor-link=Fred Skolnik|date= |year=2007|publisher=Thomson Gale|location=Detroit|isbn=978-0-02-865928-2|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/afia-aaron}}</ref> A treatise on the nature of the soul, the work contains summaries and philosophical discussions of various definitions of the soul, most notably that of  [[Johann Reuchlin]] in ''[[De Arte Cabbalistica]]''.{{r|bodies|}}

As a physician, Afia was friendly with [[Amato Lusitano]], who records how they discussed together the [[Theories of humor|source of laughter]], which Afia placed in the heart.{{r|EJ}}

