'''Convers Francis''' (November 9, 1795 – April 17, 1863) was a [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] minister from [[Watertown, Massachusetts]].

==Life and work==
He was born the son of Susannah Rand Francis and Convers Francis, and named after his father. His sister, [[Lydia Maria Child|Lydia Maria]], later became an important reformer.

Francis studied to become a minister at [[Harvard Divinity School]]. He was minister of the Watertown, Massachusetts, Unitarian Church from 1819 to 1842. Francis taught [[Theodore Parker]] beginning in 1832 and preached at his ordination ceremony in 1840.<ref>Gura, Philip F. ''American Transcendentalism: A History''. New York: Hill and Wang, 2007: 117. {{ISBN|0-8090-3477-8}}</ref> Francis encouraged Parker when his translations and books were not selling well. He wrote of his "astonishment at your labors and learning", but criticized the recent lack of interest in reading, writing "the cry is all for action—for doing something, not moping over books as they say".<ref>Gura, Philip F. ''American Transcendentalism: A History''. New York: Hill and Wang, 2007: 119. {{ISBN|0-8090-3477-8}}</ref> Both Francis and Parker joined the [[Transcendental Club]] in the 1830s, an organization which included members such as [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]], [[Henry David Thoreau]] and [[Margaret Fuller]]. Being one of the elders of the group, in fact the eldest member who was also a moderator of the Club, he influenced other members. Preaching at a time when Unitarians were breaking into sometimes-hostile factions in New England, he wrote that "the condition of things with us in the religious world is anything but pleasant... The cauldron is kept boiling, & all sorts of materials are thrown into it".<ref>Gura, Philip F. ''American Transcendentalism: A History''. New York: Hill and Wang, 2007: 148. {{ISBN|0-8090-3477-8}}</ref>

After 1842, Francis was Parkman Professor of Pulpit Eloquence at [[Harvard University|Harvard]]. His books and writings include ''Christianity as a Purely Internal Principle,'' ''[https://archive.org/stream/johneliot00fran#page/n9/mode/2up Life of John Eliot, Apostle to the Indians]'' and ''A Historical Sketch of Watertown'' (1830). He died in 1863, one year after Transcendental Club co-member Henry David Thoreau died.

