The '''Thirteen Classics''' ({{zh|t=十三經|s=十三经|p=Shísān jīng}}) is a term for the group of thirteen [[Chinese classics|classics]] of [[Confucianism|Confucian]] tradition that became the basis for the [[Imperial Examination]]s during the [[Song dynasty]] and have shaped much of [[East Asia]]n [[East Asian cultural sphere|culture and thought]].<ref>{{cite book | title = Chinese history: a manual | first = Endymion | last = Wilkinson | publisher = Harvard Univ Asia Center | edition = 2nd | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-0-674-00249-4 | pages = 475–476 }}</ref> It includes all of the [[Four Books and Five Classics]] but organizes them differently and includes the ''[[Xiao Jing|Classic of Filial Piety]]'' and ''[[Erya]]''. They are, in approximate order of composition: * ''[[Classic of Changes]]'' or ''I Ching'' (易經 ''Yìjīng'') * ''[[Book of Documents]]'' (書經 ''Shūjīng'') * ''[[Classic of Poetry]]'' (詩經 ''Shījīng'') * The Three Ritual Classics (三禮 ''Sānlǐ'') ** ''[[Rites of Zhou]]'' (周禮 ''Zhōulǐ'') ** ''[[Yili (text)|Ceremonies and Rites]]'' (儀禮 ''Yílǐ'') ** ''[[Book of Rites]]'' (禮記 ''Lǐjì'') * The Three Commentaries on the ''[[Spring and Autumn Annals]]'' ** ''[[Zuo Zhuan|The Commentary of Zuo]]'' (左傳 ''Zuǒ Zhuàn'') ** ''[[Gongyang Zhuan|The Commentary of Gongyang]]'' (公羊傳 ''Gōngyáng Zhuàn'') ** ''[[Guliang Zhuan|The Commentary of Guliang]]'' (穀梁傳 ''Gǔliáng Zhuàn'') * ''[[Analects|The Analects]]'' (論語 ''Lúnyǔ'') * ''[[Xiao Jing|Classic of Filial Piety]]'' (孝經 ''Xiàojīng'') * ''[[Erya]]'' (爾雅 ''Ěryǎ''), a dictionary and encyclopedia * ''[[Mencius (book)|Mencius]]'' (孟子 ''Mèngzǐ'')
==History== {{see also|Chinese classics}} The tradition of a defined group of "classics" in Chinese culture dates at least to the [[Warring States period]], when the ''[[Zhuangzi (book)|Zhuangzi]]'' has [[Confucius]] telling [[Laozi]] "I have studied the six classics—the ''Odes'', the ''Documents'', the ''Rites'', the ''Music'', the '' Changes'', and the ''Spring and Autumn Annals''".<ref>''Zhuangzi'', chapter 14, quoted in {{cite book | title=Writing and authority in early China | first=Mark Edward | last=Lewis | publisher=SUNY Press | year=1999 | isbn=978-0-7914-4114-5 | page=276 }}</ref> These six works were thus already considered classics by at least the 3rd century BC, although the ''[[Classic of Music]]'' did not survive the chaos of the [[Qin dynasty|Qin]] unification of China and was deemed lost during the [[Han dynasty]]. The remaining [[Five Classics]] were traditionally considered to have been edited by Confucius. Records from the late Han and [[Three Kingdoms]] period reference "seven classics", though they do not name them individually. By the [[Tang dynasty]] references to "nine classics" were common, though the nine works themselves vary depending on the source. The [[Kaicheng Stone Classics]] (833–837) comprise twelve works (all the above except the ''Mencius''). By the time of the [[Southern Song|Southern Song dynasty]], the number and specific books in the "thirteen classics" were universally established. The Thirteen Classics formed the texts used in the [[Imperial examination]]s, and their 600,000+ characters, in effect words, were generally required to be memorized in order to pass.
